The intricate web of [legislation](/Legislation) that once governed the nascent [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) offers a rather revealing glimpse into the priorities, anxieties, and occasional bureaucratic absurdities of the early 18th century. What follows is a comprehensive catalogue of the [Acts of parliament](/Act_of_parliament) enacted by the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) during the year 1717, a period marked by the consolidation of a new political entity and the ongoing challenges of its administration.

Before the grand experiment that was the [United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom) fully materialized, the British Isles were a patchwork of distinct legislative bodies. Prior to the [Acts of Union 1707](/Acts_of_Union_1707), which forged the Kingdom of Great Britain, laws were separately crafted by the ancient [Parliament of England](/Parliament_of_England) and the venerable [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland). Furthermore, the [Kingdom of Ireland](/Parliament_of_Ireland) maintained its own legislative assembly, producing its own distinct body of [Irish](/Parliament_of_Ireland) [legislation](/Legislation). For those with an insatiable appetite for historical minutiae, one can trace the legislative lineage even further back, examining [Royal statutes, etc. issued before the development of Parliament](/List_of_English_statutes) in [England](/Kingdom_of_England), providing a foundational understanding of the legal frameworks that eventually coalesced.

For the record, and because accuracy is apparently a virtue, acts passed before the Union of 1707 are to be found in the respective [list of acts of the Parliament of England](/List_of_acts_of_the_Parliament_of_England) and the [list of acts of the Parliament of Scotland](/List_of_acts_of_the_Parliament_of_Scotland). The legislative output of the [Parliament of Ireland](/Parliament_of_Ireland) also has its own dedicated chronicles.

Fast forward to the dawn of the 19th century, and with the [Acts of Union 1800](/Acts_of_Union_1800), the [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom) emerged, absorbing the functions of the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) and the [Parliament of Ireland](/Parliament_of_Ireland). Therefore, for acts passed from 1801 onwards, one must consult the [list of acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom](/List_of_acts_of_the_Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom). And because complexity is often mistaken for progress, the modern era has introduced further layers: acts of the devolved parliaments and assemblies within the contemporary [United Kingdom](/Law_of_the_United_Kingdom) – namely the [list of acts of the Scottish Parliament](/List_of_acts_of_the_Scottish_Parliament), the [list of acts of the Northern Ireland Assembly](/List_of_acts_of_the_Northern_Ireland_Assembly), and the [list of acts and measures of Senedd Cymru](/List_of_acts_and_measures_of_Senedd_Cymru) – also exist, alongside the historical [list of acts of the Parliament of Northern Ireland](/List_of_acts_of_the_Parliament_of_Northern_Ireland). One might wonder if the sheer volume of legislative history is designed to deter casual inquiry.

A brief primer on the arcane art of citation, for those who find joy in such things: The number appended to each act's title isn't merely a random flourish; it represents its chapter number within a given [parliamentary session](/Parliamentary_session). Acts are formally referenced using this chapter number, preceded by the regnal year(s) of the monarch during which that specific parliamentary session transpired. For instance, the [Union with Ireland Act 1800](/Acts_of_Union_1800) bears the citation "39 & 40 Geo. 3. c. 67." This translates to the 67th act passed during the session that commenced in the 39th year of [King George III](/George_III)'s reign and concluded in his 40th year. Modern convention, thankfully, has largely abandoned the Roman numerals for [Arabic numerals](/Arabic_numeral) in citations, so "41 Geo. 3" is now preferred over "41 Geo. III." A peculiar footnote: acts from the final session of the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) and the inaugural session of the [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom) share the rather unhelpful distinction of both being cited as "41 Geo. 3." It seems clarity was not always a top priority.

It's also worth noting that acts passed by the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) typically lacked a convenient [short title](/Short_title) in their original form. Many of these more succinct designations were retrospectively bestowed upon them by subsequent acts of the [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom), notably through the [Short Titles Act 1896](/Short_Titles_Act_1896). One can almost hear the collective sigh of relief from future legal scholars.

Before the merciful intervention of the [Acts of Parliament (Commencement) Act 1793](/Acts_of_Parliament_(Commencement)_Act_1793), which finally brought some sense to the matter on 8 April 1793, acts passed by the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) were deemed to have come into effect on the *first day* of the session in which they were passed. This legislative quirk means that the years listed below might, with a touch of historical irony, refer to the year *before* a particular act actually received [Royal assent](/Royal_assent). A system designed for maximum confusion, it would seem.

## 4 Geo. 1

The legislative activity detailed here stems from the third session of the [5th Parliament of Great Britain](/5th_Parliament_of_Great_Britain). This particular parliamentary convocation assembled on 21 November 1717 and dutifully concluded its proceedings on 21 March 1718. During this period, [George I](/George_I_of_Great_Britain) sat on the throne, navigating a realm still grappling with the recent Jacobite rising of 1715 and the inherent instability of a new Hanoverian dynasty. The political landscape was a constant balancing act between Whig dominance and Tory opposition, often tinged with lingering Jacobite sympathies. This session, like many of its contemporaries, was also conventionally referred to by the more succinct "4 G. 1," a nod to the regnal year of the monarch, [George I](/George_I_of_Great_Britain), in whose fourth year of reign these legislative efforts were undertaken.

See also: For a parallel perspective on the legislative environment across the Irish Sea, one might consult the [List of acts of the Parliament of Ireland, 1711–1720 §&#160;4 Geo. 1 (1717)](/List_of_acts_of_the_Parliament_of_Ireland,_1711%E2%80%931720). It’s always illuminating to see how different legislative bodies grappled with similar challenges, or perhaps, chose to ignore them.

### Public acts

The following [Acts of parliament](/Act_of_parliament) were considered "Public Acts," meaning they applied generally to the realm or to a significant portion of the populace, addressing matters of national importance, fiscal policy, public order, and infrastructure.

